            <div type="note">
                <head  type="title">Gertrude Atthill</head>
                <p>As granddaughter of <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s cousin, <persName corresp="#MRC">Mary Richardson</persName>, <persName corresp="#MGPBA">Atthill</persName> both
                    inherited and purchased a collection related to Ruskin family history. Items
                    from the early years included <persName corresp="#MRC">Mary Richardson</persName>&#x02BC;s diaries of <date when="1833">1833</date> and
                    <date notBefore="1840" notAfter="1841">1840&#x2013;41</date> (now at the <orgName corresp="#HUNTINGTONG">Huntington Library</orgName> <!--Entry needed here.-->), and one of her sketchbooks
                    (now at <placeName corresp="#BRANTWOOD">Brantwood</placeName>); and the portraits of <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret Ruskin</persName>, by <persName corresp="#JNORTHCOTE">James Northcote</persName>,
                    and of <persName corresp="#JJR">John James Ruskin</persName>, by <!--Entry needed here.--> Watson (both now at <placeName corresp="#BRANTWOOD">Brantwood</placeName>). <persName corresp="#JSD">Dearden</persName>
                    speculated that all the <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> drawings listed in the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Catalogue of Drawings</hi> (<title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title> 38:<!--Entry needed here.-->) as owned by
                    <persName corresp="#JJBOLDING">J. J. Bolding</persName> (<persName corresp="#MGPBA">Atthill</persName>&#x02BC;s father) belonged to her, as well, but these
                    had disappeared (see <persName corresp="#JSD">Dearden</persName>, &#x201C;Mrs Gertrude Atthill&#x201D;).</p>
            </div>
